<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-01-24T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-01-24T05:00:00-05:00" n="764" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d764">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/1393: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Merriam</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-01-24T12:00:00+02:00">January 24,
                                        1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 24—10:40
                                    a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>6. The three Arabs mentioned in paragraph 1 of my telegram 5, January
                                23, noon returned to Cairo yesterday bearing the Mufti’s consent to
                                the representation of the Nashashibi Party by two specified
                                delegates. The latter were considered unsuitable by the party heads
                                here who moreover insisted upon the party’s right to choose its own
                                delegates. The party has therefore decided to abstain from the
                                London Conference and not to recognize its findings.</p>
                            <p>The Arab delegates minus the Nashashibi sailed for England early this
                                morning.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Merriam</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>